snippet.textDisplay:
Too long: The Walking Dead

The show should've ended at season 7. It was already past it's prime technically, but I feel like Negan was the perfect villain to either brutally murder and tie the show off with the satisfying death of a universally hated character, OR, have him wipe out Rick's group and end the show on a darker note, with the message that just because you're the main character doesn't mean that the bad guy won't kill you for continually stepping on his lawn and killing his men.

snippet.textDisplay:
I honestly think everything you said perfectly fits Supernatural.
I absolutely loved Supernatural. It literally saved my life by meeting one of my best friends. I remember binge watching everything up until season 5. Where it officially was supposed to end. Fans of Supernatural know that there can't be a happy end for both main characters, because they weren't written that way. So S5 was the best ending SPN could get. And then we got more season. I continued to watch up to season 10. That's almost 200 episodes and then I stopped because it got so ridiculous. The characters I grew up to love weren't the same. They would do things without a blink which were discussed through 2 episodes back in the first seasons. The fact that all three main actors said they wanted to leave the show but didn't because they were pressured or didn't want to dissapoint the fans, already says enough.
Today season 15 (15!!!) is running on TV and the fact that I've missed 5 entire seasons breaks my heart. I tried to watch it but I cringed too hard. Instead I read the seasons summary's and - oh boy. Don't.

The fact that all three main actors said they wanted to leave the show but didn't because they were pressured or didn't want to dissapoint the fans, already says enough.
Today season 15 (15!!!) is running on TV and the fact that I've missed 5 entire seasons breaks my heart. I tried to watch it but I cringed too hard. Instead I read the seasons summary's and - oh boy. Don't.

snippet.textDisplay: I love Lucifer, but the season produced by Netflix feels like a totally different thing. Netflix has this habit of just shoving in unnecessary drama for be “groundbreaking” but it really just seems to exploit real life scenarios in an unrealistic way. Changing someone’s personality directly, or their sexuality is suddenly different in order to include more LGBT+ representation, or someone’s backstory becomes drastically different. It feels like pandering to groups of people rather than sticking to the original and carefully structured and developed plot and character designs. Pandering doesn’t make something a better show, it totally feels patronising.
